body.p:
Since the velocity is constant, the graph shows a straight, horizontal line. What is the change in the displacement
        of the object over the time interval shown? Recall that for an object that moves at a constant velocity, $@v$,
        for a time interval $@Delta @t$, the change in the displacement of the object, $@Delta @s$,
        is given by the formula
        \begin{align*}@Delta @s = @v @Delta @t.\end{align*}

In this case, the initial velocity is 12meter per second
        and the final velocity is 18meter per second, so the average velocity
        is equal to $\frac{\left(12meter per second 
          + 18meter per second \right)}{2} = 
          15meter per second$. We can now use the formula for the change
        in the displacement of the object that we used before:
        \begin{align*}@Delta @s &= @v_{\text{@average}} @Delta @t\\
      @Delta @s &= 15meter per second 
        \times 10second\\
        @Delta @s &= 150meter.\end{align*}

The line crosses the $@t$-axis at $@t = 10second$;
  the velocity goes from positive to negative; this is when the object reverses direction. The object starts out
  moving in one direction and then starts moving in the opposite direction.

answer.p:
Let’s start by finding the area between the line and the $@t$-axis for the interval 
            $\nagwaInterval{[0,1]}$. This region is a triangle, so its area, $@A_1$, is given by
            \begin{align*}@A_1 &= 4 \times 1 \times \frac{1}{2}\\
              @A_1 &= 2.\end{align*}

Now let’s find the area between the line and the $@t$-axis for the interval 
            $\nagwaInterval{[1,9]}$. This region is a trapezoid, so its area, $@A_2$,
            is given by
            \begin{align*}@A_2 &= \frac{8 + 5}{2} \times 4\\
              @A_2 &= 26.\end{align*}

Then, the displacement is given by
  \begin{align*}@Delta @s &= @A_1 - @A_2\\
    @Delta @s &= 2 - 26\\
    @Delta @s &= -24.\end{align*}

The region between the line and the $@t$-axis in the interval $\nagwaInterval{[0,1]}$
            is a triangle, so its area, which we will call $@A_1$, is equal to its height multiplied by its width
            divided by two:
            \begin{align*}@A_1 &= \frac{5 \times 1}{2}\\
              @A_1 &= 2.5.\end{align*}

The region between the line and the $@t$-axis in the interval $\nagwaInterval{[1,8]}$
            is a trapezoid, so its area, which we will call $@A_2$, is equal to its mean width multiplied by its
            height:
            \begin{align*}@A_2 &= \frac{4 + 7}{2} \times 5\\
              @A_2 &= 27.5.\end{align*}
